  "prompt": "What is compression ratio in engine?",
  "response": "Compression ratio in an engine is the ratio of the volume of the combustion chamber when the piston is at the bottom of its stroke (largest volume) to the volume when the piston is at the top of its stroke (smallest volume). It is calculated by dividing the total cylinder volume by the combustion chamber volume.\n\nFor example, a compression ratio of 10:1 means that when the piston is at the bottom of its stroke, the cylinder volume is 10 times larger than when the piston is at the top of its stroke.\n\nKey points about compression ratio:\n1. Higher compression ratios result in more power and efficiency\n2. Typically ranges from 8:1 to 14:1 in gasoline engines\n3. Diesel engines have higher compression ratios, often 14:1 to 25:1\n4. Affects engine performance, fuel efficiency, and knocking tendency\n5. Determined by cylinder and combustion chamber design\n\nThe compression ratio influences how much the air-fuel mixture is compressed before ignition, which impacts the engine's thermal efficiency and power output.",
